iv>

    <h3 style="font-family:'Cinzel Decorative',serif;color:#f08c4b;font-size:16px;margin:40px 0 20px;padding-bottom:12px;border-bottom:1px solid var(--border)">
      Elijah vs Dajjal — Parallel Characteristics
    </h3>

    <div style="overflow-x:auto;margin-bottom:40px">
    <table class="compare-table" style="width:100%">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>CHARACTERISTIC</th>
          <th style="color:#4aab7a">✝ ELIJAH (Biblical)</th>
          <th style="color:#f08c4b">☽ DAJJAL (Islamic)</th>
          <th>MATCH</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="trait-label">Control over rain/weather</span></td>
          <td>Shut up rain for 3.5 years (1 Kings 17:1, James 5:17)</td>
          <td>Commands rain and crops — follows are fed, opponents face drought (Sahih Muslim 2934)</td>
          <td><span class="match-badge match-strong">STRONG</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="trait-label">Fire from heaven</span></td>
          <td>Called fire from heaven 3 times (1 Kings 18:38, 2 Kings 1:10-12) — his defining miracle</td>
          <td>Performs spectacular miracles including fire. False Prophet (Dajjal-adjacent) calls fire from heaven (Rev 13:13)</td>
          <td><span class="match-badge match-partial">NOTABLE</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="trait-label">Never died / unnatural existence</span></td>
          <td>Taken to heaven in chariot of fire without dying (2 Kings 2:11). Must return to die (Heb 9:27).</td>
          <td>Dajjal is said to be imprisoned on an island, waiting — al-Jassasah hadith (Sahih Muslim 2942). Has an unnatural pre-history before appearing.</td>
          <td><span class="match-badge match-partial">SUGGESTIVE</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="trait-label">Appears at end of age</span></td>
          <td>Malachi 4:5 — "before the great and dreadful day of the LORD." Matthew 17:11 — future confirmed by Jesus.</td>
          <td>One of the major Signs of the Hour. Appears near the end of history before the Day of Judgment.</td>
          <td><span class="match-badge match-strong">STRONG</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="trait-label">Killed near Jerusalem / Israel</span></td>
          <td>Two Witnesses killed in Jerusalem (Rev 11:7-8). "The great city" = Jerusalem.</td>
          <td>Dajjal killed by Isa at the Gate of Ludd (Lod) — modern-day Israel, near Jerusalem (Sahih Muslim 2937).</td>
          <td><span class="match-badge match-strong">GEOGRAPHIC MATCH</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="trait-label">Resurrection / taken up</span></td>
          <td>Two Witnesses resurrected after 3.5 days and ascend to heaven as enemies watch (Rev 11:11-12).</td>
          <td>Dajjal is killed and stays dead. <strong>No resurrection.</strong></td>
          <td><span class="match-badge match-inverse">DIVERGENCE</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="trait-label">Claims divinity</span></td>
          <td>Elijah never claims to be God — he is God's servant. "The LORD, He is God!" (1 Kings 18:39)</td>
          <td>Dajjal explicitly claims to be God/Messiah. This is his defining characteristic (Sahih Muslim 2933).</td>
          <td><span class="match-badge match-inverse">MAJOR DIVERGENCE</span></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><span class="trait-label">Moral character</span></td>
          <td>Righteous, humble, obedient to God. One of the greatest prophets.</td>
          <td>The Great Deceiver. Evil. Sent by Satan. Anti-God.</td>
          <td><span class="match-badge match-inverse">OPPOSITE</span></td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    </div>

    <h3 style="font-family:'Cinzel Decorative',serif;color:var(--gold);font-size:16px;margin:40px 0 20px;padding-bottom:12px;border-bottom:1px solid var(--border)">
      The Real Bombshell — The False Prophet IS the Dajjal-Elijah Connection
    </h3>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Revelation 13:13</strong> says the False Prophet (second beast) "performed great signs, even <em>causing fire to come down from heaven</em>." Calling fire from heaven is <strong>Elijah's signature miracle</strong> — no other Biblical figure is specifically associated with it. This suggests the False Prophet is an <strong>Elijah-impersonator</strong> — a counterfeit Elijah who performs the real Elijah's miracles in service of the Antichrist.
    </div>

    <div class="three-cols" style="margin-top:30px">
      <div class="lens-card theologian">
        <div class="lens-icon">🔥</div>
        <h3>The Counterfeit Elijah Reading</h3>
        <p>Satan always counterfeits God's plan. The real Elijah (Two Witnesses) returns to call people to repent. Satan sends a Counterfeit Elijah (False Prophet / Dajjal) who performs the same miracles — fire from heaven, control of rain — to deceive people into following the Antichrist (Mahdi).</p>
        <p>Under the inversion thesis: The real Two Witnesses (Elijah+Moses) are the ones the Islamic world calls Dajjal's associates or enemies. The counterfeit Elijah (Islamic Isa who performs signs) is what the Bible calls the False Prophet.</p>
        <div class="verdict-line">
          <div class="verdict-dot" style="background:var(--gold)"></div>
          <span style="color:var(--gold)">Most theologically coherent mapping</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="lens-card islamic-scholar">
        <div class="lens-icon">☽</div>
        <h3>Islamic Response</h3>
        <p>From an Islamic perspective, Elijah (Ilyas) is a respected prophet mentioned in the Quran (6:85, 37:123-132). He is not identified with Dajjal — quite the opposite. The Dajjal is the enemy of all prophets.</p>
        <p>However, the Islamic framework does warn that the Dajjal will perform convincing miracles that will deceive even the faithful. A figure appearing with miraculous signs who claims prophetic authority would fit what Islam warns people to reject.</p>
        <div class="verdict-line">
          <div class="verdict-dot" style="background:var(--danger)"></div>
          <span style="color:var(--danger)">Rejected — Ilyas/Elijah is honored in Islam</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="lens-card secular">
        <div class="lens-icon">🔭</div>
        <h3>Secular Analysis</h3>
        <p>The fire-from-heaven miracle shared by Elijah, the Two Witnesses, and the False Prophet suggests a common mythological archetype of the thunder-prophet — a figure who commands divine fire. This appears in Zoroastrian (Ahura Mazda), Greek (Zeus), and Semitic traditions.</p>
        <p>The Dajjal's imprisonment-before-emergence parallels Elijah's translation to heaven — both involve figures who exit normal history and return at a critical moment. Whether this reflects prophetic identity or archetypal storytelling is the irreducible question.</p>
        <div class="verdict-line">
          <div class="verdict-dot" style="background:var(--gold)"></div>
          <span style="color:var(--gold)">Interesting archetype — unprovable as identity</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="conclusion-box" style="margin-top:40px">
      <h3>Verdict on the Elijah-Dajjal Hypothesis</h3>
      <p>The strongest connection is <strong>indirect</strong>: Elijah's signature miracle (fire from heaven) appears in the False Prophet of Revelation 13 — suggesting the False Prophet is a counterfeit Elijah, not that the Dajjal IS Elijah literally.</p>
      <p>The fatal problem remains: Elijah is righteous and never claims divinity. The Dajjal explicitly claims to be God — the opposite moral character. Under the inversion thesis this could mean: what Islam calls the greatest evil (claiming to be God), the Biblical framework sees as the greatest good (God actually being present). But this requires a theological leap that goes beyond the textual evidence.</p>
      <p><strong>What this hypothesis adds to the study:</strong> It reveals that the fire-from-heaven miracle is a deliberate eschatological signature — appearing in Elijah, the Two Witnesses, and the False Prophet — suggesting all three are part of a connected prophetic thread. The Dajjal's miracle-performing profile maps better to the False Prophet than to Elijah himself. This actually <em>strengthens</em> the four-figure mapping from the main debate.</p>
    </div>
  </section>


  <div class="divider"></div>

  <!-- Temporarily hidden; keep this section in source control for later restoration. -->
  <section id="hidden-treasures" hidden aria-hidden="true">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-tag">§ IX — Deep Excavation</span>
      <h2>Hidden Treasures — Connections Nobody Talks About</h2>
      <p>Beyond the main debate. Eight genuine textual parallels between Islam and the Bible that are either overlooked, underexplored, or genuinely shocking. Strength-rated honestly — no hallucinations.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- CONNECTION 1: GOG AND MAGOG -->
    <div style="border:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:40px;overflow:hidden">
      <div style="padding:20px 28px;background:rgba(201,168,76,0.08);border-bottom:2px solid var(--gold);display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center">
        <div>
          <span style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;letter-spacing:3px;color:var(--gold-dim)">CONNECTION 01</span>
          <h3 style="font-family:'Cinzel Decorative',serif;color:var(--gold);font-size:18px;margin-top:4px">Gog & Magog / Ya'juj wa Ma'juj — Same Figure, Same Name, Both Traditions</h3>
        </div>
        <span class="match-badge match-strong" style="font-size:13px;padding:6px 14px">STRENGTH: IRONCLAD</span>
      </div>
      <div style="padding:24px 28px">
        <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:24px;margin-bottom:20px">
          <div>
            <p style="color:var(--biblical-blue-light);font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;letter-spacing:2px;margin-bottom:10px">✝ BIBLE</p>
            <p><strong>Ezekiel 38-39:</strong> "Gog, of the land of Magog" leads a massive coalition from the north to invade Israel. Destroyed by God directly — fire, brimstone, earthquake, plague. Birds and animals eat the bodies for 7 months (Ezekiel 39:12-14).</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px"><strong>Revelation 20:7-8:</strong> After the millennium, Satan deceives "Gog and Magog" — nations from the four corners of the earth — to surround Jerusalem. Destroyed by fire from heaven.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <p style="color:var(--islamic-green-light);font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;letter-spacing:2px;margin-bottom:10px">☽ QURAN + HADITH</p>
            <p><strong>Quran 18:94-97, 21:96:</strong> Ya'juj wa Ma'juj are trapped behind an iron-and-copper wall built by Dhul-Qarnayn. "Until when Gog and Magog are let loose and they swarm down from every hill" (21:96).</p>
            <p style="margin-top:10px"><strong>Sahih Muslim 2937:</strong> After Isa kills Dajjal, Ya'juj wa Ma'juj emerge. They drink the Sea of Galilee dry. They shoot arrows into the sky claiming to kill the inhabitants of heaven. Allah destroys them with a worm in their necks. Birds carry their bodies away.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="callout" style="margin:0">
          <strong>The Buried Bombshell:</strong> Both traditions share the same NAMES (Gog/Magog = Ya'juj/Ma'juj — linguistically identical), the same timing (after the Messiah defeats the primary enemy), the same destruction method (divine intervention, not human military), and the same gruesome aftermath (birds eating bodies — Ezekiel 39:17, Islamic hadith). This is not a parallel — this is the <em>same event</em> described in both scriptures with the same proper nouns. The only difference is sequence placement.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- CONNECTION 2: DOME OF THE ROCK -->
    <div style="border:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:40px;overflow:hidden">
      <div style="padding:20px 28px;background:rgba(201,76,76,0.08);border-bottom:2px solid var(--danger);display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center">
        <div>
          <span style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;letter-spacing:3px;color:var(--danger)">CONNECTION 02</span>
          <h3 style="font-family:'Cinzel Decorative',serif;color:var(--danger);font-size:18px;margin-top:4px">The Dome of the Rock — An Abomination Already Standing?</h3>
        </div>
        <span class="match-badge match-partial" style="font-size:13px;padding:6px 14px">STRENGTH: STRONG — HISTORICALLY GROUNDED</span>
      </div>
      <div style="padding:24px 28px">
        <p><strong>The text:</strong> Matthew 24:15 — Jesus says: "When you see the abomination of desolation, spoken of by the prophet Daniel, standing in the holy place — let the reader understand — then let those in Judea flee." The Greek word for "standing" (histemi) implies a permanent, erected structure — not just a person.</p>
        <p style="margin-top:12px"><strong>What happened in 691 CE:</strong> Caliph Abd al-Malik built the Dome of the Rock directly on the Temple Mount — the "holy place" — on the exact site of the Jewish Temple. The Dome's interior inscription, still visible today in Arabic around the octagonal arcade, reads: <em>"Praise be to God who begets no son and has no partner in his dominion... Far be it from His glory that He should have a son."</em> — A direct, deliberate denial of the central claim of Christianity, inscribed permanently in the holiest location in Christendom.</p>
        <p style="margin-top:12px"><strong>The historical witness:</strong> Sophronius, the Christian Patriarch of Jerusalem in 637 CE, when he saw Omar's intentions for the Temple Mount, reportedly exclaimed: "Verily, this is the Abomination of Desolation as spoken of by Daniel the prophet." This is recorded in early church sources.</p>
        <div class="warning-callout" style="margin-top:16px">
          <strong>Honest caveat:</strong> Most scholars argue the Abomination of Desolation is a future event involving a rebuilt Temple and the Antichrist setting up an idol. The Dome of the Rock does not "cause desolation" in the technical prophetic sense. But the coincidence of an Islamic structure with explicit anti-Christ-divinity inscriptions permanently occupying the exact site of the Jewish Temple — where the Antichrist is prophesied to set himself up — is theologically striking and cannot be entirely dismissed.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- CONNECTION 3: CHANGING TIMES AND LAWS -->
    <div style="border:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:40px;overflow:hidden">
      <div style="padding:20px 28px;background:rgba(74,122,199,0.08);border-bottom:2px solid var(--biblical-blue-light);display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center">
        <div>
          <span style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;letter-spacing:3px;color:var(--biblical-blue-light)">CONNECTION 03</span>
          <h3 style="font-family:'Cinzel Decorative',serif;color:var(--biblical-blue-light);font-size:18px;margin-top:4px">Daniel 7:25 — "He Will Change Times and Laws" — Already Done?</h3>
        </div>
        <span class="match-badge match-strong" style="font-size:13px;padding:6px 14px">STRENGTH: STRONG</span>
      </div>
      <div style="padding:24px 28px">
        <p><strong>Daniel 7:25</strong> describes the Antichrist: "He will speak against the Most High and oppress his holy people and try to <em>change the set times and the laws</em>. The holy people will be delivered into his hands for a time, times and half a time."</p>
        <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:20px;margin-top:16px">
          <div style="padding:16px;border:1px solid var(--border);background:rgba(74,122,199,0.05)">
            <p style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;color:var(--biblical-blue-light);margin-bottom:8px">CHANGING THE TIMES</p>
            <p>Islam introduced the <strong>Hijri (lunar) calendar</strong>, replacing the Julian/Gregorian solar calendar across all conquered territories. Every date, legal document, contract, and religious observance shifted to a new calendar system beginning from Muhammad's migration (622 CE). Entire civilizations changed how they measured time.</p>
          </div>
          <div style="padding:16px;border:1px solid var(--border);background:rgba(74,122,199,0.05)">
            <p style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:11px;color:var(--biblical-blue-light);margin-bottom:8px">CHANGING THE LAWS</p>
            <p><strong>Sharia law</strong> replaced Roman law, Byzantine Christian law, Mosaic law, and tribal customary law across the entire Middle East, North Africa, Persia, and Spain. Every legal system in the conquered world was abolished and replaced with Islamic jurisprudence. This is the most comprehensive legal transformation in human history.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p style="margin-top:16px;color:var(--text-dim);font-style:italic">Whether this is a past fulfillment, a future fulfillment through the Mahdi's global Sharia, or a general characteristic — the specificity of "times and laws" maps precisely onto Islam's historical and eschatological program. No other world system more literally "changed the set times and the laws" across entire civilizations.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- CONNECTION 4: MARK OF THE BEAST / FOREHEAD -->
    <div style="border:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:40px;overflow:hidden">
      <div style="padding:20px 28px;background:rgba(201,168,76,0.08);border-bottom:2px solid var(--gold);display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center">
        <div>
          <span style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;letter-spacing:3px;color:var(--gold-dim)">CONNECTION 04</span>
          <h3 style="font-family:'Cinzel Decorative',serif;color:var(--gold);font-size:18px;margin-top:4px">Two Competing Marks on Foreheads — Ezekiel, Revelation & the Zebibah</h3>
        </div>
        <span class="match-badge match-partial" style="font-size:13px;padding:6px 14px">STRENGTH: PROVOCATIVE — SPECULATIVE</span>
      </div>
      <div style="padding:24px 28px">
        <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr 1fr;gap:16px;margin-bottom:16px">
          <div style="padding:14px;border:1px solid var(--border)">
            <p style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;color:var(--gold);margin-bottom:8px">EZEKIEL 9:4</p>
            <p style="font-size:14px">God tells an angel: "Go throughout the city of Jerusalem and put a <em>mark on the foreheads</em> of those who grieve over the detestable things done in it." — A protective mark on the righteous foreheads BEFORE judgment.</p>
          </div>
          <div style="padding:14px;border:1px solid var(--border)">
            <p style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;color:var(--biblical-blue-light);margin-bottom:8px">REVELATION 7:3, 13:16</p>
            <p style="font-size:14px">God's servants are <em>sealed on their foreheads</em> (Rev 7:3). The Beast demands a <em>mark on the right hand or forehead</em> (Rev 13:16). Two competing marks — God's seal vs Beast's mark — both on the forehead.</p>
          </div>
          <div style="padding:14px;border:1px solid var(--border)">
            <p style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;color:var(--islamic-green-light);margin-bottom:8px">THE ZEBIBAH</p>
            <p style="font-size:14px">The <em>zebibah</em> (prayer callus) — a dark mark on the forehead developed from years of Islamic sujood (prostration in prayer) — is considered a sign of piety in Islam. Quran 48:29 describes believers with "their marks on their faces from the effects of prostration."</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p style="color:var(--text-dim);font-style:italic;font-size:14px">The question: Is the zebibah — a literal mark on the forehead produced by Islamic worship — the "mark of the beast" that Revelation describes? Or is it God's seal, marking the faithful? The same physical location. Two completely opposite theological interpretations. The text does not specify whether the mark is visible or invisible — only its location.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- CONNECTION 5: THE FATAL WOUND HEALED -->
    <div style="border:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:40px;overflow:hidden">
      <div style="padding:20px 28px;background:rgba(240,140,75,0.08);border-bottom:2px solid #f08c4b;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center">
        <div>
          <span style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;letter-spacing:3px;color:#f08c4b">CONNECTION 05</span>
          <h3 style="font-family:'Cinzel Decorative',serif;color:#f08c4b;font-size:18px;margin-top:4px">The Fatal Wound That Was Healed — The Ottoman Caliphate</h3>
        </div>
        <span class="match-badge match-partial" style="font-size:13px;padding:6px 14px">STRENGTH: MODERATE — MODERN ARGUMENT</span>
      </div>
      <div style="padding:24px 28px">
        <p><strong>Revelation 13:3:</strong> "One of the heads of the beast seemed to have had a fatal wound, but the fatal wound had been healed. The whole world was filled with wonder and followed the beast."</p>
        <p style="margin-top:12px"><strong>Richardson's argument:</strong> The Ottoman Caliphate — the last Islamic empire holding the title of Caliph, ruling from Jerusalem, commanding the Muslim world — was formally abolished on <strong>March 3, 1924</strong> by Mustafa Kemal Atatürk. This was described by Muslims worldwide as a catastrophic blow to Islam — a "fatal wound" to the Islamic political-religious body. The Caliphate had existed in some form for 1,300 years. Its abolition was sudden and traumatic.</p>
        <p style="margin-top:12px"><strong>The healing:</strong> A revived Caliphate — which both ISIS attempted (2014) and which remains the explicit goal of multiple Islamist movements — would be the "fatal wound healed." If a Mahdi figure arises and re-establishes the Caliphate globally, Revelation 13:3 would describe Muslims worldwide following him in wonder at the restoration of what seemed permanently destroyed.</p>
        <div class="warning-callout" style="margin-top:16px">
          <strong>Honest caveat:</strong> This is a modern interpretive argument, not a direct textual parallel. The "heads" in Revelation 13 are debated — they may refer to Roman emperors, world empires, or something else entirely. But the structural fit is striking.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- CONNECTION 6: PSALM 83 COALITION -->
    <div style="border:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:40px;overflow:hidden">
      <div style="padding:20px 28px;background:rgba(76,201,122,0.08);border-bottom:2px solid var(--agree);display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center">
        <div>
          <span style="font-family:'JetBrains Mono',monospace;font-size:10px;letter-spacing:3px;color:var(--agree)">CONNECTION 06</span>
          <h3 style="font-family:'Cinzel Decorative',serif;color:var(--agree);font-size:18px;margin-top:4px">Psalm 83 — Written 3,000 Years Ago, Describes Today's Map Exactly</h3>
        </div>
        <span class="match-badge match-strong" style="font-size:13px;padding:6px 14px">STRENGTH: STUNNING — GEOGRAPHICALLY EXACT</span>
      </div>
      <div style="padding:24px 28px">
        <p>Psalm 83:1-8 records a prayer about a coalition of nations consp